Patch Set 31:

> Shilong,
 > 
 > I see why we need to mark the OSC lock as granted, but I am looking
 > at the assert and that seems to be buffered i/o which is finding an
 > extent under one of these locks, which is lockless.
 > 
 > Isn't that wrong...?  What is happening there, if not that?

Patrick,

I think the buffer IO might come from that sometimes we might fall to buffer IO
See codes in 

__generic_file_aio_write()

      if (io_is_direct(file)) {
                loff_t endbyte;
                ssize_t written_buffered;

                written = generic_file_direct_write(iocb, iov, &nr_segs, pos,
                                                        ppos, count, ocount);
                /*
                 * If the write stopped short of completing, fall back to
                 * buffered writes.  Some filesystems do this for writes to
                 * holes, for example.  For DAX files, a buffered write will
                 * not succeed (even if it did, DAX does not handle dirty
                 * page-cache pages correctly).
                 */
                if (written < 0 || written == count || IS_DAX(inode))
                        goto out;

                pos += written;
                count -= written;
                written_buffered = generic_file_buffered_write(iocb, iov,
                                                nr_segs, pos, ppos, count,
                                                written);


Maybe the problem is we fall into buffer IO here? If that is case we might still need lock
for DIO...
